<TEXT>
alaskas attorney general asked exxon on 
wednesday to allow the state to question its employees under oath 
about how potentially significant documents on the exxon valdez oil 
spill were destroyed 
attorney general douglas baily said the destruction of 
computerized files at exxon co usa headquarters in houston was 
potentially a loss of devastating proportions to the 
investigation of the nations worst oil spill 
i assume that exxon is as interested as we are in allowing the 
public to have the full access the full knowledge of exactly what 
it was that led to the destruction of those documents baily said 
at a news conference 
exxon is under state and federal court orders to preserve its 
records of the march 24 tanker spill in prince william sound 
company officials have said the documents were destroyed 
accidentally but that other copies may exist 
i have no idea at this point whether it was deliberate or 
whether it was unintentional but i think theres a big question out 
there in the minds of the public as to whether it was deliberate or 
accidental baily said 
the court orders prevent parties planning litigation against 
exxon from undertaking depositions and other forms of pretrial 
discovery until the courts can settle the issues and procedures 
involved baily said 
the attorney general is giving exxon until noon thursday to 
respond to his request he said he got no reply from exxon officials 
wednesday 
in the event that they do not agree to that stipulation we 
will ask the court to alter its order so we can undertake that 
limited discovery at the present time baily said adding that 
quick action was essential 
bailys news conference came after exxon headquarters in houston 
had closed for the night and calls there went unanswered late 
wednesday 
a former exxon computer technician kenneth a davis told the 
new york times last week that he inadvertently destroyed the files 
davis alleged that his superiors negiligent protection of the 
records caused the accident 
davis was fired june 8 the day after the destruction was 
discovered the times reported 
the destroyed material included internal memos and 
wordprocessing documents from exxon shipping co which owns the 
exxon valdez and exxon usa the newspaper said 
baily said the documents cover a twoweek period about six to 
eight weeks after the spill a time when exxon was determining how 
to defend its actions 
loss of the documents could affect others who may become involved 
in lawsuits against the oil company such as fishermen businesses 
and alaska natives hurt by the spill he said 
if the documents cannot be recovered there are a variety of 
sanctions that could be imposed by the courts against exxon but 
their severity would depend on what the documents held baily said 
</TEXT>
