<TEXT>
a soviet nuclear submarine that caught fire 
last week off norway leaked small amounts of radiation and its 
reactor may have come close to a meltdown a norwegian scientist 
said 
traces of radioactive iodine 131 were found in a water sample 
taken two days after the june 26 fire aboard the echo ii class 
vessel 70 miles off norways coast in the norwegian sea state 
researchers said tuesday 
knut gussgard director of the norwegian nuclear energy safety 
board said the submarine apparently suffered what is called a 
loss of coolant accident which is what can lead to a meltdown 
gussgard said the radioactive iodine is a byproduct of nuclear 
fission which means the core must have leaked coolant exposing 
uranium fuel rods that may have burst or even began to melt 
support for the possibility of a meltdown came from finn 
ugletveit of the norwegian radiation hygiene institute the 
chances that this kind of radiation came from anything but the core 
are slim he said 
ugletveit whose institute conducted the radiation tests said 
the radioactive iodine 131 was diluted by seawater and we expect 
it to disappear completely very quickly all other air and water 
tests showed no radiation 
tass on monday said four sailors were hospitalized and were being 
examined for possible radiation poisoning but the news agency said 
today that the four were healthy and have no excess radiation 
tass quoted lt gen igor sinoplanikov of the soviet defense 
ministry as saying a decontamination of the submarines crew was 
carried out june 28 the day the vessel returned to soviet naval 
base at murmansk this was done to dispel fears of the sailors and 
their relatives sinoplanikov said 
in a message to the norwegian government recieved on friday 
moscow said the reactors primary cooling system leaked but the 
systems design guaranteed the security of the reactor the 
norwegian news agency ntb reported 
gussgard said the size of a submarine reactor is about 2 percent 
of a power plant such as chernobyl which caused an environmental 
disaster after a 1986 nuclear accident 
a submarine reactor is so small that we probably wouldnt see 
an environmental catastrophe but if there was a meltdown off 
norway we might experience radiation levels similar to those that 
passed over norway and sweden after chernobyl he said 
chernobyl fallout contaminated livestock and fish in parts of 
norway and sweden as well as parts of eastern europe 
with two accidents in three months among the 100 nuclear 
submarines of the soviet north fleet base near norway gussgard said 
a major accident no longer seems theoretical 
on april 7 a soviet mike class nuclear submarine sank off 
norway killing 42 soviet sailors 
