<TEXT>
labor costs rose more slowly last year in the 
united states than in all but one of the nations 11 major economic 
competitors the labor department said 
the rise in us labor costs 03 percent from 1987 to 1988 
was dwarfed by such increases as 17 percent in taiwan and 112 
percent in south korea 
of the 11 competitors only france bettered the us performance 
recording a decline of 08 percent the bureau of labor statistics 
said 
while american workers were still earning more than employees in 
most of the other countries the fall in the value of the dollar 
meant that a japanese worker was catching up fast to his us 
counterparts 
the average japanese worker cost the employer 1314 an hour in 
1988 a 105 percent increase over 1987 the average in the united 
states was 1390 
in eight western european countries the costs were already 
higher than in the united states 1943 in norway for example and 
1807 in west germany 
in south korea however the cost of an average hours labor was 
only 245 and in taiwan 271 
that is an employer could hire more than five taiwanese or south 
korean workers for the cost of hiring one american this helps 
explain why some factories have moved production lines out of the 
united states to those pacific rim countries 
not all labor costs go to workers as wages the labor department 
figures include employer contributions to private plans and payroll 
taxes for social services such as pensions and health care from 
which workers benefit these expenses are generally higher in 
western europe than in the united states and higher in the united 
states than in the countries on the pacific rim 
here are the percentage changes for each of the 12 countries 
surveyed increases for all but france the bureau did not give the 
1988 cost for an hours labor in all the increases are bases on 
costs measured in dollars because of exchangerate fluctuations 
the percentages might be different for costs measured in local 
currencies 
taiwan 17 percent britain 118 percent south korea 112 
percent canada 109 percent japan 105 percent sweden 79 
percent denmark 34 percent italy 29 percent west germany 18 
percent the netherlands 1 percent the united states 03 percent 
france minus 08 percent 
