<TEXT>
fine art prices are going going gonzo this 
auction season soaring through the ceiling when the gavel comes 
down but even as the art market booms some experts fear the 
picture may not stay so pretty 
a lot of people are being taken in by this sort of fever 
said george goldner a curator and top buyer at the j paul getty 
museum the nations richest the longer it goes on the more it 
resembles a bubble that one day will burst 
for now the inflation is inescapable as even goldner will 
attest he paid 325 million for a 16th century painting last 
month more than tripling the record for an old master at auction 
and all that glitters is not goldners 
records were set for more than three dozen modern postmodern 
and impressionist painters at sales in may including 479 million 
for a picasso selfportrait an 800 percent increase from its 1981 
price only one painting has done better a van gogh that drew 539 
million in 1987 
an 18 century american bookcase desk sold in may for 121 
million quadrupling the record for a piece of furniture the 
reported buyer was neither museum nor gallery but a texas 
financier robert m bass 
a catskill mountains landscape sold for 825 million tops for 
an old american painting a frederic remington bronze brought 44 
million a new height for american sculpture the birds of 
america etchings by john james audubon sold for 396 million an 
increase of 2 million in less than two years 
such prices are reflected in thousands of lesser sales rippling 
through the art world in a delicious shudder at least for sellers 
sothebys auction house the worlds biggest gaveled off 18 
billion in goods last year up by 400 million from 1987 and this 
year is far bigger 
its awesome its mindboggling said milton esterow 
publisher of artnews magazine art has become an international 
currency the market has exploded its a revolution a renaissance 
like weve never seen before 
but the glee is not universal art experts say the soaring sums 
are pricing many museums out of the market leaving them unable to 
expand or upgrade their collections some say auction hype has 
falsely inflated some prices 
its simple and easy buy something and youll get rich this 
is the message of the auction rooms said goldner its the 
wrong message and people eventually are going to get hurt by it 
there will be a day when the market will shake out and bad modern 
paintings wont be worth what people are paying for them today 
the reason for arts price explosion is simple because of 
worldwide economic good times many people have much more money as 
some of that cash migrated to art prices rose drawing finer art 
to the market and raising prices even higher and 1986 federal tax 
changes limited the benefits of donating art to museums putting 
even more works on the market 
additionally said harvey katz an art market analyst for the 
investment firm salomon brothers inc the auction houses have 
improved their marketing techniques catalogs are less intimidating 
major works are sent on tour before sales bidding is simpler and 
telephone bids are accepted 
as the auction houses have become more accessible theyve 
captured more and more business said katz one result christies 
auction house is rumored as a takeover target and sothebys is 
splitting its stock two for one 
but goldner said auction house promotions can misrepresent the 
value of some pieces particularly costly modern art and he called 
sothebys practice of lending money to buyers a dangerous trend that 
inflates the market and increases the perception of art as a 
speculative commodity 
john marion chairman of sothebys north america maintained that 
buyers still are primarily collectors drawn to certain works not 
investors seeking profit and he said marketing ultimately does 
not create sales 
what weapons do we use to get people into bidding they do 
spend real money marion said sothebys willingness to loan 
buyers some of that money he added is no different from a banks 
loan to a home buyer 
another concern is the art booms effect on public museums many 
of which are finding themselves unable to afford major purchases or 
pressed to sell some works to private buyers which removes the art 
from public view 
such was the case for the walker art center in minneapolis a 
modern art gallery that sold the 825 million catskill landscape 
by frederic edwin church to finance purchases of modern works the 
painting was on loan to the minneapolis institute of art which had 
it on display a dealer bought it 
this was an issue we wrestled with long and hard said erwin 
kelena board member of the walker and its acquisitions committee 
chairman is it our responsibility to keep a 19th century painting 
on public view even if not in our institution or to maximize 
acquisitions for our own collection 
while the latter concern prevailed kelen said the painting 
likely will outlive its new owners and be returned to a museum 
goldner however said he feared the growing concept of art as a 
commodity would work against that outcome 
the sad fact is that a lot of people who call themseves 
collectors today are investors he said and instead of giving 
their collections toward the end of their life to a museum to put on 
display they see their apotheosis as being a successful sale at 
sothebys 
marion for his part is looking forward to sothebys greatest 
sale yet an estate auction next fall that includes 44 paintings 
valued at 1 million or more each including a van gogh a picasso 
and nine monets the total take should easily exceed 100 million 
the fall he said looks to be very very strong 
</TEXT>
