<DOCNO> AP890705-0211 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
a major us construction firm signed a contract 
wednesday to join in a 479 million building project in downtown 
tokyo 
morrisonknudsen international co will join with hazamagumi 
ltd one of japans largest civil engineering firms to build an 
18story office and residential tower for shuwa corp a large 
japanese real estate firm 
the company a division of boise idahobased morrisonknudsen 
corp has established an office in tokyo and obtained a japanese 
construction permit which the ministry of construction says only 
nine us construction firms currently possess 
amid complaints that japans construction market was closed to 
foreign companies the japanese government signed an agreement in 
may 1988 to allow us companies to participate in public works 
projects here 
richard e kohne chairman and chief executive officer of 
morrisonknudsen said this will be his firms first project in 
japan although it has operated in many countries abroad he said 
morrisonknudsen would receive between 15 and 35 percent of the work 
in the project 
in looking for a japanese partner he added morrisonknudsen 
interviewed a dozen potential contractors and chose hazama because 
they are the closest in traditions and culture with our company 
shuwa president shigeru kobayashi said his company had promised 
former us commerce secretary c william verity it would help us 
firms participate in the japanese market 
during the last two years shuwa has actively sought us clients 
with the help of the us department of commerce and the us 
embassy in japan toshihiko okino a spokesman for shuwa said 
the office tower project is shuwas second contract with a us 
firm for work in japan in march it awarded an 112 billion yen 
80 million contract to a joint venture between the turner corp 
and kumagai gumi of japan 
shuwa plans at least two more projects in which it will invite 
us firms to participate okino added 
shuwa also owns 25 billion in office and hotel space in the 
united states making it one of the largest japanese owners of us 
real estate 
 
