<TEXT>
federal officials announced wednesday that three 
former thrift executive agreed to plead guilty to bank fraud charges 
and that a former savings and loan president was indicted on three 
similar counts 
the latest charges bring to 26 the number of people indicted this 
year by the dallas bank fraud task force compared with 23 people in 
all of 1988 the task force investigates cases in north texas said 
bob gillham agentincharge of the dallas fbi office 
of those indicted 20 have been senior officers owners or vice 
presidents of banks or savings and loans gillham said 
the threecount indictment names bob r franks former president 
and director of northpark savings association in richardson and 
accuses him of scheming to defraud northpark of funds and 
misapplying 138000 of the thrifts money 
franks faces up to 15 years in prison and a 500000 fine 
the three who agreed to plead guilty were 
john h roberts jr former president and owner of summit 
savings association of dallas to charges of bank fraud and 
misapplication of funds the indictment filed june 8 alleges he 
schemed to defraud summit of 45 million and misapplied 1 million 
of summit funds 
federal officials contend roberts arranged for a borrower to 
obtain a loan to buy a jet for roberts personal use the indictment 
said roberts planned to have summit make a 200000 downpayment on 
the airplane and charge the payment as a draw against a prior 25 
million construction loan to a summit borrower without the 
borrowers knowledge or consent 
roberts faces up to 10 years in prison and a 15000 fine or 
twice the amount of the gain or loss 
joseph r smith former vice president and loan officer of 
sunbelt savings association of dallas to one count of conspiracy to 
defraud the federal home loan bank board by disguising the true 
financial condition of sunbelts loan portfolio and defrauding the 
internal revenue service 
the indictment alleges smith received 125000 from a sunbelt 
real estate transaction but smith did not report it on his 1985 tax 
returns 
smith faces up to five years imprisonment and a 250000 fine or 
twice the amount of the gain or loss 
kenneth clive hood former board chairman of century investments 
and former vice president of western savings association to two 
counts of conspiring to defraud the irs by creating artificial 
losses for amchase financial corp to offset large income gains 
hood also agreed to plead guilty to making a false statement in 
connection with an 114 million loan from sunbelt savings 
association 
he faces up to seven years in prison and a fine of 500000 
</TEXT>
